<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36208g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36208g">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36208g"> 208(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Peacheyite, one sus-/pender, no bone buttons</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Mennonites.]</font> It was Jacob Amman, too, who instituted the custom of wearing hooks instead of buttons. It will be recalled that buttons in that day were made entirely of bones, and bones came from animals, and the true Mennonites, like the Dukhobors, believed in using nothing from animals which they could do without &hellip; Two steps above the Nebraskas <font color="green">[varieties of Amish in Mifflin County, Pennsylvania]</font> are the &ldquo;<mark>Peacheyites</mark>,&rdquo; who may wear a single suspender, provided it is home-made. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 423</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c09117c" href="c09all.htm#c09117c">VI.C.09:117(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
